K-Nearest Neighbors Algorithm using Scikit-Learn

The K-nearest neighbors (KNN) algorithm is a type of supervised machine learning algorithms. KNN is extremely easy to implement in its most basic form, and yet performs quite complex classification tasks.

It is a lazy learning algorithm since it doesn't have a specialized training phase. Rather, it uses all of the data for training while classifying a new data point or instance.

KNN is a non-parametric learning algorithm, which means that it doesn't assume anything about the underlying data. This is an extremely useful feature since most of the real world data doesn't really follow any theoretical assumption e.g. linear-separability, uniform distribution, etc.

Theory

The intuition behind the KNN algorithm is one of the simplest of all the supervised machine learning algorithms. It simply calculates the distance of a new data point to all other training data points. The distance can be of any type e.g Euclidean or Manhattan etc. It then selects the K-nearest data points, where K can be any integer. Finally it assigns the data point to the class to which the majority of the K data points belong.

Let's see this algorithm in action with the help of a simple example. Suppose you have a dataset with two variables, which when plotted, looks like the one in the following figure.

Manhattan distance between 2 points is the distance along the axis, like you measure the distance in a right angled way. Usually used in circuits to measure the distance wires take; as the wires cannot run in between the circuit-boards.

Dataset

Income (k$) Loan Amount (k$) Class
5 10 Non-Defaulter
10 15 Non-Defaulter
15 14 Non-Defaulter
25 45 Non-Defaulter
30 12 Non-Defaulter
55 53 LoanDefaulter
60 78 LoanDefaulter
70 80 LoanDefaulter
75 90 LoanDefaulter
85 70 LoanDefaulter

Your task is to classify a new data point 'X' into the 'Non-Defaulter' or 'LoanDefaulter' class. The coordinates of the data point are X1 = 45 and X2 = 50. Suppose the value of K is 3. The K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) algorithm starts by calculating the distance from point X to all the existing points. It then identifies the 3 nearest points with the smallest distances to point X. These nearest points are highlighted in the figure below.

The final step of the KNN algorithm is to assign the new point to the class to which the majority of the three nearest points belong. From the figure above, we can see that two of the three nearest points belong to the class 'LoanDefaulter' while one belongs to the class 'Non-Defaulter'. Therefore, the new data point will be classified as 'LoanDefaulter'.

KNN Hyperparameters

Hyperparameter Meaning / Purpose Typical Values to Try in Industry
n_neighbors Number of nearest neighbors used to classify a new data point. Smaller values focus on local structure, larger values generalize more. 3 15 (odd numbers like 3, 5, 7, 11 are common to avoid ties)
weights How the influence of neighbors is calculated.
'uniform': all neighbors have equal weight.
'distance': closer neighbors have higher influence.		 'uniform', 'distance' (both are often tested; 'distance' sometimes gives better results in unevenly distributed data)
algorithm The algorithm used to compute nearest neighbors.
'auto': automatically chooses the best method.
'ball_tree', 'kd_tree', 'brute': specific search algorithms for optimization.		 'auto' (default and works well in most cases); 'kd_tree' or 'ball_tree' for large datasets with continuous variables
leaf_size Affects the speed of tree-based neighbor searches (ball_tree, kd_tree). Larger sizes reduce tree depth but increase computation per node. 20 50 (default is 30, and it's often fine-tuned when optimizing search performance)
p Power parameter for the distance metric:
p=1: Manhattan distance
p=2: Euclidean distance.		 1 or 2 (Euclidean distance p=2 is most common; Manhattan sometimes used in high-dimensional spaces)
metric The distance metric to use when calculating neighbor distances. 'minkowski' is a general case covering most distances. 'minkowski', 'euclidean', 'manhattan' (Euclidean is most common for continuous numeric data)
metric_params Additional arguments for the distance metric. Typically left as None, unless using specialized metrics. None (custom parameters are rare; standard metrics usually suffice)
n_jobs Number of parallel jobs to run during neighbor search.
None: use a single core.
-1: use all available cores.		 -1 (use all cores for speed during training and prediction on large datasets)
In[10]:
# Implementing KNN
# https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier.html

# class sklearn.neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5, *, weights='uniform', algorithm='auto', leaf_size=30, p=2, metric='minkowski', metric_params=None, n_jobs=None)

from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5)
knn.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predicting the labels for the training and testing data
y_pred_train = knn.predict(X_train)
y_pred_test = knn.predict(X_test)

# Evaluating the model
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
print("Training accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred_train))
print("Testing accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_test))

1. Precision

Meaning: Out of all the predictions for a particular class, how many were actually correct?

Formula:

$$ \text{Precision} = \frac{\text{True Positives (TP)}}{\text{True Positives (TP)} + \text{False Positives (FP)}} $$

Example:

  • For class A, predicted as A 10 times.
  • Actually correct 8 times (True Positives), and wrong 2 times (False Positives).
$$ \text{Precision for A} = \frac{8}{8 + 2} = 0.8 $$

2. Recall

Meaning: Out of all actual instances of a class, how many were correctly predicted?

Formula:

$$ \text{Recall} = \frac{\text{True Positives (TP)}}{\text{True Positives (TP)} + \text{False Negatives (FN)}} $$

Example:

  • For class A, total 12 actual A cases.
  • Correctly predicted as A 8 times, missed 4 times (False Negatives).
$$ \text{Recall for A} = \frac{8}{8 + 4} = 0.67 $$

3. F1-Score

Meaning: Harmonic mean of Precision and Recall. Balances both in one score.

Formula:

$$ \text{F1-score} = 2 \times \frac{\text{Precision} \times \text{Recall}}{\text{Precision} + \text{Recall}} $$

Example: Using Precision = 0.8 and Recall = 0.67 from above,

$$ F1 = 2 \times \frac{0.8 \times 0.67}{0.8 + 0.67} \approx 0.73 $$

4. Support

Meaning: The actual number of occurrences of the class in the dataset.

Example: If class A appeared 12 times, its support is 12.

5. Accuracy

Meaning: Overall how many predictions were correct, across all classes.

Formula:

$$ \text{Accuracy} = \frac{\text{Total Correct Predictions}}{\text{Total Predictions}} $$

Example: If 90 predictions were made and 85 were correct,

$$ \text{Accuracy} = \frac{85}{90} \approx 0.94 $$

6. Macro Average

Meaning: Average of Precision, Recall, or F1-score calculated separately for each class, then averaged. Does not consider class imbalance.

Example: If F1-scores for classes A, B, and C are 0.70, 0.80, and 0.90,

$$ \text{Macro Avg F1} = \frac{0.70 + 0.80 + 0.90}{3} = 0.80 $$

7. Weighted Average

Meaning: Average of Precision, Recall, or F1-score for all classes, weighted by the number of true instances (support) for each class. This accounts for class imbalance.

Example: If F1-scores and supports are:

  • A: F1=0.70, support=10
  • B: F1=0.80, support=30
  • C: F1=0.90, support=60

Weighted Avg F1 =

$$ \frac{(0.70 \times 10) + (0.80 \times 30) + (0.90 \times 60)}{10 + 30 + 60} = \frac{7 + 24 + 54}{100} = 0.85 $$

Summary Table:

Metric Purpose Formula Example
Precision Correct positive predictions / all positive predictions TP / (TP + FP)
Recall Correct positive predictions / actual positives TP / (TP + FN)
F1-score Harmonic mean of Precision and Recall 2 (P R) / (P + R)
Support Number of actual samples in the class count of samples
Accuracy Correct predictions / total predictions (TP + TN) / total
Macro avg Simple average across all classes sum of metric / no. of classes
Weighted avg Weighted by the number of samples in each class sum of (metric support) / total samples

Summary of Results on Iris Dataset

  • The model performs very well overall, especially for Setosa and Virginica.
  • Small misclassifications exist between Versicolor and other classes, which is common because Versicolor and Virginica sometimes have overlapping feature values.
  • These are strong results for a simple KNN model, demonstrating that KNN works effectively on the well-behaved, clean Iris dataset.

Comparing Error Rate with the K Value

In the training and prediction section we said that there is no way to know beforehand which value of K that yields the best results in the first go. We randomly chose 5 as the K value and it just happen to result in 100% accuracy.

One way to help you find the best value of K is to plot the graph of K value and the corresponding error rate for the dataset.

In this section, we will plot the mean error for the predicted values of test set for all the K values between 1 and 40.

To do so, let's first calculate the mean of error for all the predicted values where K ranges from 1 and 40. Execute the following script:

In[]:
error = [] # Initialize an empty list to store error values
# This list will be used to store the mean error for each K value

# Calculating error for K values between 1 and 40
for i in range(1, 40):  
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=i)
    knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
    pred_i = knn.predict(X_test)
    error.append(np.mean(pred_i != y_test)) # Calculate the mean error for each K value
    #here != compares 2 ndarray objects 
    # return value is array of true/false i.e 0/1 values , of which we are 
    # finding the mean values.
    
    
    # The above script executes a loop from 1 to 40. 
    # In each iteration the mean error for predicted values of test set 
    # is calculated and the result is appended to the error list.
    
# The next step is to plot the error values against K values.
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))  
plt.plot(range(1, 40), error, color='red', linestyle='dashed', marker='o',  
         markerfacecolor='blue', markersize=10)
plt.title('Error Rate K Value')  
plt.xlabel('K Value')  
plt.ylabel('Mean Error')   
plt.show()

Interpretation of the K Value vs. Mean Error Plot

Key Observations:

  1. Initial Drop in Error:

    • At K=1, the error rate is relatively higher (~0.08).
    • As K increases to 3, the error drops sharply and reaches a low point (~0.025).

  2. Flat Low-Error Region:

    • Between K=3 and K=17, the error rate remains consistently low. This suggests that the model performs well in this range.
    • This flat section indicates stability, meaning the model predictions are not overly sensitive to changes in K in this range.

  3. Increase in Error Beyond K=17:

    • After K=17, the error starts increasing, becoming more unstable and higher beyond K=20.
    • This happens because as K increases, the algorithm starts including too many neighbors, some of which may belong to other classes, leading to wrong classifications.

  4. High Error at Very Large K:

    • From K=35 onwards, the error rate rises sharply, indicating poor model performance. A very large K oversimplifies the decision boundary (over-generalization).

Conclusion: Optimal K Selection

  • Optimal K Range: K values between 3 and 15 give the lowest and most stable error rates in your plot.

  • A commonly chosen K is where the error first stabilizes at its lowest point:

    • K = 5 or K = 7 could be ideal starting points.
    • Choosing odd K values like 3, 5, or 7 is preferred to avoid ties in voting.

  • Avoid too small K (K=1):

    • May cause the model to overfit (high variance).

  • Avoid too large K (>20):

    • May cause the model to underfit (high bias).

Final Recommendation:

Try K = 5 or K = 7, and possibly cross-validate within the 3 to 15 range to select the final K value.

In[]:

Pros:

  1. Simple and easy to implement.
  2. Lazy learning algorithm that stores the training data and performs no upfront model training. New data can be added without retraining.
  3. Requires tuning of only two hyperparameters: the number of neighbors (K) and the distance metric.

Cons:

  1. Performs poorly on high-dimensional datasets due to the curse of dimensionality.
  2. Computationally expensive during prediction, especially for large datasets, as distances to all training points must be computed.
  3. Does not naturally handle categorical features, as distance metrics are designed for continuous data.

Happy Learning
